Bellabeat Analysis

Erick Smith

2023-04-25

Case study: FitBit Tracker Data For Bellabeat in R

Hello everyone, this case of study show you what are some trends inside the products of Bellabeat company.

About the company

Urška Sršen and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products. Sršen used her background as an artist to develop beautifully designed technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits.

Products

Bellabeat launched multiple products, but for my Case Study I will choose only wellness tracker. Wearable trackers are an increasingly popular tool among healthy adults and are used to facilitate self-monitoring of physical activity.

  • Bellabeat app: The Bellabeat app provides users with health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. This data can help users better understand their current habits and make healthy decisions. The Bellabeat app connects to their line of smart wellness products.

  • Leaf: Bellabeat’s classic wellness tracker can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip. The Leaf tracker connects to the Bellabeat app to track activity, sleep, and stress.

  • Time: This wellness watch combines the timeless look of a classic timepiece with smart technology to track user activity, sleep, and stress. The Time watch connects to the Bellabeat app to provide you with insights into your daily wellness.

  • Spring: This is a water bottle that tracks daily water intake using smart technology to ensure that you are appropriately hydrated throughout the day. The Spring bottle connects to the Bellabeat app to track your hydration levels.

  • Bellabeat membership: Bellabeat also oﬀers a subscription-based membership program for users. Membership gives users 24/7 access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep, health and beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

Ask

Identifying the problem of the stakeholders, they need to guide a marketing strategy using product of Bellabeat. In this analysis I will answer this questions:

  1. What are some trends in smart device usage?
  2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  3. How could these trends help inﬂuence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Prepare

I use public data that explores smart device users’ daily habits.Speciﬁc data set:

FitBit Fitness Tracker Data (CC0: Public Domain, dataset made available through Mobius): This Kaggle data set contains personal ﬁtness tracker from thirty ﬁtbit users.

The data are including:

  • Minute-level output for physical activity.

  • Heart rate.

  • Sleep monitoring.

  • Daily activity.

  • Steps.

  • Heart rate.

Visualizations

Steps analysis

steps_per_hour_AM <- steps_filtered %>%
  mutate(hora = hms(hora)) %>%
  mutate(hour_interval = cut(hour(hora), breaks = seq(0, 24, by = 1), right = FALSE)) %>% 
  group_by(hour_interval) %>% 
  
  filter(am_pm == "AM") %>%
  select(hora,Steps,am_pm)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `hour_interval`
  #summarize(mean_steps = mean(Steps))

ggplot(data = steps_per_hour_AM, aes(x = hour_interval, y=Steps)) + 
  #geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="blue") + 
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "Average number of steps per interval of 1 hours.", 
       x = "Hours in the morning", 
       y = "Number of steps")

steps_per_hour_PM <- steps_filtered %>%
  mutate(hora = hms(hora)) %>%
  mutate(hour_interval = cut(hour(hora), breaks = seq(0, 24, by = 1), right = FALSE)) %>% 
  group_by(hour_interval) %>% 
  
  filter(am_pm == "PM") %>%
  select(hora,Steps,am_pm)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `hour_interval`
  #summarize(mean_steps = mean(Steps))

ggplot(data = steps_per_hour_PM, aes(x = hour_interval, y=Steps)) + 
  #geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="blue") + 
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "Average number of steps per interval of 1 hours.", 
       x = "Hours in the Afternoon", 
       y = "Number of steps")

Based on my analysis, I have observed that Bellabeat clients tend to walk more in the afternoon as compared to the mornings. Specifically, clients tend to walk between 5:00 pm - 7:00 pm and 11:00 pm - 12:00 am in the evening, while in the morning, they tend to walk between 8:00 am - 11:00 am.

steps_mean <- steps_filtered %>%
  mutate(hora = hms(hora)) %>%
  mutate(hour_interval = cut(hour(hora), breaks = seq(0, 24, by = 1), right = FALSE)) %>% 
  group_by(hour_interval) %>% 
  filter(am_pm == "AM") %>%
  summarize(promedio = mean(Steps))

ggplot(data = steps_mean, aes(x = hour_interval, y=promedio, group=1)) + 
  #geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="blue") +
  geom_point()+
  geom_line(colour="red")+
  labs(title = "Average number of steps in the Morning", 
       x = "Hours in the Morning", 
       y = "Average number of steps")

Calories analysis

d_activity_c_s <- d_activity %>%
  filter(TotalSteps > 0)
  ggplot(data=d_activity_c_s, aes(x=TotalSteps,y=Calories))+
    geom_point()+
    geom_smooth()+
    labs(title="Relation Calories - steps",
         x="Steps")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

There is a direct positive correlation between the number of steps taken during the day and the amount of calories burned. In other words, the more steps a person takes, the more calories they are likely to lose.

d_activity_c_s <- d_activity %>%
  filter(TotalSteps > 0)
  ggplot(data=d_activity_c_s, aes(x=TotalDistance,y=Calories))+
    geom_point()+
    geom_smooth()+
    labs(title="Relation Calories - Steps",
         x= "Distance in Km")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Similar to the previous point there is a positive relation between the distance a person walk and the number of calories they burn. In other word, the farther a person walks, more calories lose.

Findings

After analysing the data, the following insights would help influence Bellabeat Marketing strategy:

  • According to the World Health Organization (WHO), it is recommended that adults strive to take at least 10,000 steps per day as a general guideline for daily physical activity. However, the average number of steps taken by Bellabeat customers is 7,601, which suggests that they are falling short of this target by over 2,399 steps.

  • The sedentary time is significantly higher when compared to active exercise.

  • On average customers take 49 minutes before falling asleep

  • The customers are light active (Very active, Moderately active and Light active)

  • The average heart rate of customers is 77.3 beats per minute. This falls within the typical resting heart rate range of 60 to 100 beats per minute for most healthy adult women.

  • Bellabeat clients tend to walk more in the afternoon as compared to the mornings. Specifically, clients tend to walk between 5:00 pm - 7:00 pm and 11:00 pm - 12:00 am in the evening, while in the morning, they tend to walk between 8:00 am - 11:00 am.

  • Data average:

    ○ Total Steps: 7816

    ○ Total Distance: 5.63 m customers walk for each step 71.87 cm average

    ○ Active Distance: 1.54 km

    ○ Active Minutes: 22.03 min - is recommended 75 minutes vigorous-intensity

    ○ Sedentary Minutes: 978.6 min - 16.3 hrs

    ○ Sleep time: 429.2 min - 7.15 hrs

    ○ Time in bed: 458.5 min - 7.64 hrs

    ○ Heart rate: 77.33 beats per minute

Recommendations

The Bellabeat app is a comprehensive tool that helps women enhance both their personal and professional lives by promoting healthy habits and providing personalized recommendations for daily routines. For instance:

  1. To help clients achieve their weight loss goals, the app can calculate the number of calories burned per day and send progress updates to the user.

  2. The app offers customized scheduling recommendations for activities such as sleep, exercise, and work. It also provides guidance on how to break bad habits.

  3. If the wellness tracker detects that a user is having trouble sleeping, the app offers tutorials on how to sleep better.

  4. The app provides the equivalent walking distance needed based on the type of active distance recorded (Light, Moderate, Active).

  5. Bellabeat encourages physical activity through various events and activities.
